The kinetic energy \( T \) and potential energy \( V \) are given by:
\begin{align}
    T &= v^2 \dot{u}^2 + 2 \dot{v}^2 \label{eq:T} \\
    V &= u^2 - v^2 \label{eq:V}
\end{align}

The Lagrangian \( L \) is defined as:
\begin{equation}
    L = T - V = v^2 \dot{u}^2 + 2 \dot{v}^2 - u^2 + v^2 \label{eq:L}
\end{equation}

The partial derivatives of the Lagrangian are:
\begin{align}
    \frac{\partial L}{\partial \dot{u}} &= 2v^2 \dot{u}, \quad \frac{\partial L}{\partial u} = -2u \label{eq:partial_u} \\
    \frac{\partial L}{\partial \dot{v}} &= 4 \dot{v}, \quad \frac{\partial L}{\partial v} = 2v(\dot{u}^2 + 1) \label{eq:partial_v}
\end{align}

The equations of motion are derived from the Euler-Lagrange equations:
\begin{align}
    \frac{d}{dt} \left( \frac{\partial L}{\partial \dot{u}} \right) - \frac{\partial L}{\partial u} &= 0 \label{eq:eom_u} \\
    \frac{d}{dt} \left( \frac{\partial L}{\partial \dot{v}} \right) - \frac{\partial L}{\partial v} &= 0 \label{eq:eom_v}
\end{align}

These yield the following equations of motion:
\begin{align}
    2 \frac{d}{dt}(v^2 \dot{u}) + 2u &= 0 \quad \text{or} \quad v^2 \ddot{u} + 2 \dot{u} \dot{v} + 2u = 0 \label{eq:motion_u} \\
    2 \ddot{v} + v(\dot{u}^2 + 1) &= 0 \label{eq:motion_v}
\end{align}

