\begin{equation}
    T = \frac{1}{2} M \dot{x}'^2 + \frac{1}{2} m (\dot{x}'^2 + 2 \dot{x} \dot{x}' \cos \theta + \dot{x}^2) \tag{4}
\end{equation}

while the potential energy takes the form:

\begin{equation}
    V = -mgx \sin \theta \tag{5}
\end{equation}

and the Lagrangian is given by:

\begin{equation}
    L = \frac{1}{2} M \dot{x}'^2 + \frac{1}{2} m (\dot{x}'^2 + 2 \dot{x} \dot{x}' \cos \theta + \dot{x}^2) + mgx \sin \theta \tag{6}
\end{equation}

The equations of motion are:

\begin{align}
    \frac{d}{dt} \left( \frac{\partial L}{\partial \dot{x}} \right) - \frac{\partial L}{\partial x} &= 0 \tag{7} \\
    \frac{d}{dt} \left( \frac{\partial L}{\partial \dot{x}'} \right) - \frac{\partial L}{\partial x'} &= 0 \tag{8}
\end{align}

yielding:

\begin{align}
    m(\ddot{x}' \cos \theta + \ddot{x}) - mg \sin \theta &= 0 \tag{9} \\
    M \ddot{x}' + m(\ddot{x}' + \ddot{x} \cos \theta) &= 0 \tag{10}
\end{align}

Solving (9) and (10), we find:

\begin{align}
    \ddot{x} &= \frac{g \sin \theta}{1 - \frac{m \cos^2 \theta}{M + m}} = \frac{(M + m) g \sin \theta}{M + m \sin^2 \theta} \tag{11} \\
    \ddot{x}' &= -\frac{g \sin \theta \cos \theta}{\frac{M + m}{m} - \cos^2 \theta} = -\frac{m g \sin \theta \cos \theta}{M + m \sin^2 \theta} \tag{12}
\end{align}

which are in agreement with the equations of problem (2.14) derived from Newtonian mechanics.

