    T = \frac{1}{2} m (\dot{x}^2 + \omega^2 x^2)
\end{equation}
because the velocity of the bead on the wire is at right angle to the linear velocity of the wire. The potential energy \( V \) is:
\begin{equation}
    V = mgx \sin \omega t
\end{equation}
because \(\omega t = \theta\), where \(\theta\) is the angle made by the wire with the horizontal at time \( t \), and \( x \sin \theta \) is the height above the horizontal position. Therefore, the Lagrangian \( L \) is:
\begin{equation}
    L = \frac{1}{2} m (\dot{x}^2 + \omega^2 x^2) - mgx \sin \omega t
\end{equation}

The partial derivatives of the Lagrangian are:
\begin{align}
    \frac{\partial L}{\partial \dot{x}} &= m \dot{x}, \\
    \frac{\partial L}{\partial x} &= m \omega^2 x - mg \sin \omega t
\end{align}

Lagrange's equation is given by:
\begin{equation}
    \frac{d}{dt} \left( \frac{\partial L}{\partial \dot{x}} \right) - \frac{\partial L}{\partial x} = 0
\end{equation}

This becomes the equation of motion:
\begin{equation}
    \ddot{x} - \omega^2 x + g \sin \omega t = 0
\end{equation}

which has the solution:
\begin{equation}
    x = A e^{\omega t} + B e^{-\omega t} + \frac{g}{2\omega^2} \sin \omega t
\end{equation}
where \( A \) and \( B \) are constants of integration determined from initial conditions. At \( t = 0 \), \( x = 0 \) and \( \dot{x} = 0 \):
\begin{equation}
    x(0) = 0, \quad \dot{x}(0) = 0
\end{equation}

Further, the velocity \(\dot{x}\) is:
\begin{equation}
    \dot{x} = \omega (A e^{\omega t} - B e^{-\omega t}) + \frac{g}{2\omega} \cos \omega t
\end{equation}

Using the initial conditions in equations (7) and (9), we obtain:
\begin{align}
    0 &= A + B \\
    0 &= \omega (A - B) + \frac{g}{2\omega}
\end{align}

Solving these equations, we find:
\begin{align}
    A &= -\frac{g}{4\omega^2}, \\
    B &= \frac{g}{4\omega^2}
\end{align}

The complete solution for \( x \) is:
\begin{equation}
    x = \frac{g}{4\omega^2} \left( e^{-\omega t} - e^{\omega t} + 2 \sin \omega t \right)
\end{equation}

