\end{align}

The Hamiltonian $H$ is given by:

\begin{equation}
    H = \sum_i \dot{q}_i \frac{\partial L}{\partial \dot{q}_i} - L \quad \text{or} \quad H + L = 2T = \sum_i \dot{q}_i \frac{\partial L}{\partial \dot{q}_i}
\end{equation}

Thus, the kinetic energy $2T$ is:

\begin{equation}
    2T = \dot{\theta} \frac{\partial L}{\partial \dot{\theta}} + \dot{\phi} \frac{\partial L}{\partial \dot{\phi}} = \frac{1}{m l^2} \left( p_\theta^2 + \csc^2 \theta \, p_\phi^2 \right) \tag{3}
\end{equation}

Therefore, the Hamiltonian $H$ is:

\begin{equation}
    H = T + V = \frac{1}{2 m l^2} \left( p_\theta^2 + \csc^2 \theta \, p_\phi^2 \right) - m g l \cos \theta \tag{4}
\end{equation}

The coordinate $\phi$ is ignorable, and therefore $p_\phi$ is a constant of motion determined by the initial conditions. We are then left with only two canonical equations to be solved. The canonical equations are:

\begin{align}
    \dot{q}_j &= \frac{\partial H}{\partial p_j} \\
    \dot{p}_j &= -\frac{\partial H}{\partial q_j}
\end{align}

Specifically, we have:

\begin{align}
    \dot{\theta} &= \frac{\partial H}{\partial p_\theta} = \frac{p_\theta}{m l^2} \tag{5} \\
    \dot{p}_\theta &= -\frac{\partial H}{\partial \theta} = \frac{p_\phi^2}{m l^2} \frac{\cos \theta}{\sin^3 \theta} - m g l \sin \theta \tag{6}
\end{align}

where $p_\phi$ is a constant of motion. By eliminating $p_\theta$, we can immediately obtain a second-order differential equation in $\theta$ as in prob. (7.10).

