\begin{equation}
    H = \frac{1}{2}p^2 + \frac{1}{2}\omega^2 q^2
\end{equation}

The equations of motion are derived from Hamilton's equations:
\begin{align}
    \frac{\partial H}{\partial p} &= \dot{q} = p \label{eq:motion1} \\
    \frac{\partial H}{\partial q} &= -\dot{p} = \omega^2 q \label{eq:motion2}
\end{align}

Differentiating equation \eqref{eq:motion1}, we have
\begin{equation}
    \ddot{q} = \dot{p} = -\omega^2 q \label{eq:motion3}
\end{equation}

Let \( q = x \), then equation \eqref{eq:motion3} can be rewritten as
\begin{equation}
    \ddot{x} + \omega^2 x = 0 \label{eq:harmonic}
\end{equation}

This is the equation for a one-dimensional harmonic oscillator. The general solution is
\begin{equation}
    x = A \sin(\omega t + \varepsilon) + B \cos(\omega t + \varepsilon) \label{eq:solution}
\end{equation}

which can be verified by substituting equation \eqref{eq:solution} into equation \eqref{eq:harmonic}. Here, \( A \), \( B \), and \( \varepsilon \) are constants to be determined from initial conditions.

